{"/service/ndnp/nbu/batch_nbu_irisvirginica_ver01/data/sn86063459/00280778564/1907100401/0295.xml":{"full_text":"WM. ROBERTSON, JR.\nSTOVES, FURNITURE\nAN D CARPETS\nCash or Credit\nWhat Do You Know\nAbout This?\nA Suit or Overcoat Made\nto Order for\nNo More\nFrom Sheeps Back to Your Back\n0 I ISSUED BY .AUTHORITY OF C\nREGISTERED P S\nI I! J\nWORLD'S GREATEST TAILORS\nLincoln, Nebraska.\nUse the Best\nIt b\nLIHBEITY\nFLOW\nIt is made in Lincoln and every sack\nis warranted to give satisfaction.\nBARBER FOSTER\nSK00030S09000OeO03K-000OeOM\nYour Cigars Should Bear This Label..\nSO?\n-fc MM\nunion-made Cigars. r n I\ntthtS Cl1rtlrt. if an eyr. mm t m hd flts ttntah.\nhimi c no w jutoihlm Miadm4iwtM.il nt out Imim mmmm\nUtMClMft I. IN III 1 tkuM. 1 tott\nll mill! HI illl Mm uw U m\nIt is insurance against sweat shop and\ntenement goods, and against disease.\n00000000030000roSO000\nThe Lincoln Wallpaper Paint Co.\nA Strictly talon Simp\nKi Modem Decorators, Wail\nPaper, Mouldings, Etc. Soffit.\nAlto Pbtne 1975\n1450 O STREET\nNo Less\n145 So. 13th Street,\nmjUi'IW.\n1 r;'\nToronto. An increase of two cents\nan hour has been granted to the\nstreet car men.\nMadrid. Unionism in Spain com\nprises 56.905 members, distributed\nthrough 373 local unions.\nProvidence, R. I. By refusing the\ndemand for an increase of 31 per\ncent in wages the Pawtucket Mfg.\ncompany lost 300 of its employes.\nCanton, O.-Xonunion bands were\nnot discriminated against at the dedi\ncation exercises of the McKinley\nmonument at Canton, September 30.\nLondon. The Amalgamated Society\nof British Engineers will, after this\nyear, cease attending the trades union\ncongress, absenting itself for at least\nfour years.\nCopenhagen. This city is also af\nfected by a strike of telegraphers. The\nwomen operators have struck for an\nadvance in pay. The government\nagreed, providing the women would do\nwork similar to that being done by\nmen. Some of those who accepted\nhave been put to repairing wires.\nClayton. The general condition of\nthe glass trade in South Jersey is sat\nisfactory, and in some branches of the\nindustry it is a difficult matter to sup\nply enough skilled men to meet the re\nquests of the manufacturers. The\nbusiness outlook is bright, and com\nparatively few who want work are\nnow out of employment.\nPittsburg, Pa. Ten thousand mill\nworkers in the Pittsburg district will\nget more pay under the new scale of\nprices just announced by the wage\ncommittee of the workmen and em\nployers, the change being based on\nthe selling price of iron for the pre\nvious three months. The average in\ncrease will be about ten per cent.\nXew Haven, Conn. Frank A. Mct\nGee, of Worcester, Mass., organizer of\nthe International Molders' union, and\nJohn A. Dunn, secretary of the local\nunion of the craft, were arrested,\ncharged with intimidation of non\nunion men who are at work in McLa\ngon's foundry, where a strike of 40\nmen has been in force for some time.\nMahanoy City, Pa. To terminate a.\nstrike of motormen and conductors,\nwhich has tied up the line for three\nmonths, business men and retired citi\nzens in the affected district bought\nthe Shamokin-Mount Carmel electric\nrailway, which runs 20 miles through\na populous territory. The men quit\nwork when the officials refused the\nmotormen permission to sit down at\ntheir work, a custom generally in\nvogue through this region.\nWashington. The annual investiga\ntion of the bureau of Tabor Into wages\nand the retail prices of food shows\nthat in the principal manufacturing\nand mechanical industries of the coun\ntry the average wages per hour in\n1906 were 4.5 per cent, higher than in\n1905; the regular hours of labor per\nweek were 0.5 per cent. lower, and the\nnumber of employes in the establish\nments investigated was seven per cent,\ngreater. The average full-time week,\nly earnings per employe in 1906 were\n3.9 per cent, greater than in 1905.\nChicago. Woman strikers among\nthe telegraphers carried on a syste\nmatic campaign to raise funds for\nstrike benefits. Lillian Sullivan, 18\nyears old, formerly a check girl at the\noffice of the Western Union company,\nheaded a delegation of 25 young wom\nen who canvassed the city for\nmoney. They sold pencil portraits of\nthemselves and also spoke before the\nmeetings of local labor unions and\nsolicited funds to carry on the strike.\nCoffeyville, Kan. The ministers of\nthis place have adopted a union sjale\nof prices for conducting funerals, and\nthey propose extending their organiza\ntion to all portions of the state. Re\ncently one tZ the ministers was caHod\nto attend a funeral at a neighboring\n,oint. H paid his own car fare,\ntired a liver?' lean and bought h:s\nown dinner after the funeral. The\nresult was a meeting of the Minis'\nte'.ial association and the adoption of\na five-dollar fee a fui.eral or no serv\nice. City of Mexico. Owing to the re\ncent numerous strikes on the part of\nmill hands and railroad operatives\nthroughout the Mexican republic, the\ngovernment has decided to take dras\ntic action against the leaders and agi\ntators in all cases where the men are\nadvised to walk out for trivial causes\nas has been alleged In the late strikes\nIf, after Investigation, the government\nis convinced that the calling of a strike\nis a mere pretext to attain ascend\nancy over the employer, the striking\nworkmen and the leaders will be ex\niled to prison to the island of Las Tres\nMarias, in the Pacific ocean, 100 miles\noff the coast of the Tepic territory.\nPittsburg, Pa. State officers began\nan investigation into the claim that\nbetween 7,000 and 8,000 miners and\nbreakers now employed in mines are\nunder the legal age required by the\nchild labor laws.\nChicago. Twenty union printers\nstarted to work at \"cases\" which they\nhave not touched for more than two\nyears in the composing rooms of the\nFaithorn Printing company\". The type\nsetters were involved in one of the\nlongest strikes on record in Chicago,\nwhich was ended when the firm\nagreed to adopt the eight-hour work\ning day.\nSt. Louis, Mo. After an all day con\ntest behind closed doors, delegates to\nthe twelfth biennial conference of the\nInternational Association of Machin\nists voted to oust Delegate George\nWarner of New York city, who was\naccused of receiving $10,000 a year\nfrom the Erie railway to use his influ\nence in preventing strikes. Warner\nfrankly admits that he did receive\nquarterly payments of $2,500 from the\nErie railroad to use his political influ\nence against the widening and deepen\ning of the Erie canal.\nRochester, N. Y. Delegates of the\nUnited Teamsters of America have\nreturned home, following the close of\nthe annual convention. The following\nis the result of the election: Presi\ndent, John Sheridan of Chicago; vice\npresidents, A. L. St. Clair, St. Louis;\nVal. Hoffmann, New York; John Mas-\nton, Rochester; George Prescott, New\nYork; Thomas Martin, New York;\nFrank Ray, Chicago; Alfred Spencer,\nChicago; general secretary-treasurer,\nW. H. Ashton, New York. The New\ncharter of the organization was ac\ncepted. The' next convention will be\nheld in St. Louis.\nNew York. With a threatened\nstrike of engineers on all coastwise\nand transatlantic steamships flying\nthe American flag, there appeared a\nnew difficulty for the small fleet of\nAmerican \"vessels in deep-sea service.\nThe demands of the Marine Engineers'\nassociation of this city called for a ten\nper cent, increase in wages of en\ngineers and oilers. The proposed\nschedule was adopted at a conference\nof,., similar organizations on the At\nlantic coast last July, and Secretary\nJames J. Waters, of the local union.\nsaid that practically all engineers In\nAmerican vessels were back of the de\nmand. The steamship companies have\nconsidered the proposition and were\nunanimous in opposing the increase.\nChicago. John Sheridan, who has\nbeen elected president of the United\nTeamsters of America, who have just\nconcluded their session at Rochester,\nN. Y., has been conspicuous \"in the or-\nanization for some time. He has\nheld the office of vice president and\nhe also has been at the head of im\nportant committees. Mr. Sheridan is\nwell known in organized labor circles\nin Chicago, and is credited. with hav\ning formulated to a material extent\nthe new charter adopted by the na\ntional body.\nChattanooga, Tenn. The Georgia\nIron Coal company indefinitely shut'\ndown its plant at Rising Fawn. The\nfurnace gave employment to 400 men.\nTwo reports are afloat as to the cause\nof the shut-down, one being the ad\nverse legislation by the last legisla\nture, and the other attributes -the shut\ndown to disagreement among the com\npany's officials.\nChicago. Strikes in the coal mines\nof Illinois are threatened by the In\ndustrial Workers of the World, which\nunion announced a program of \"rev\nolution\" in a fight which is to be\nwaged against the unions of the Unit\ned Mine Workers, headed by John\nMitchell, throughout the southern\npart of the state. Amocg the things\nadvocated in connection with the\nmovement was the immediate abroga\ntion of contracts with employers and\nthe abolishing of rich union treasur\nies, which were declared by delegates\nto be \"curses\" upon workingmen. The\n$850,000 fund collected by the Illinois\nminers was described by Secretary\nW. E. Trautmann as \"employers'\nmoney.\" He said it was deposited in\nbanks owned by mine operators and\ntherefore was tainted.\nVictoria, B. C. Engineers in the\nlumber camps of British Columbia are\nreceiving $80 to $85 a month with\nboard. A few months ago they re\nceived but $50.\nNew York. A general lockout of\nthe 3,000 fur workers belonging to the\nFur Workers' union was ordered by\nthe Fur Manufacturers' association of\nNew York, owing to trouble caused by\npetty strikes for recognition of the\nunion and other causes. The locked\nout fur workers, among whom are a\nnumber of women, must apply for\nwork individually before they can be\nre-employed.\nBOASTS OF THE LABEL.\nFremont Herald Proud to Carry It at\nthe Paper's Masthead.\nThe Herald with, this issue pins at\nIts mast-head the union label the\nemblem of labor that shows the sym\npathy with, an interest in unionism\neverywhere.\nWith respect to the local differences\nbetween union labor and our con\ntemporary, the Herald has no part.\nWhatever other newspapers or job of\nfices do or have to do with union\nprinters is no fight of ours. Nor will\nthis newspaper knowingly say aught\nto inflame any feeling that may exist\ntetween other newspapers and their\nemployes.'\nThe union label at the head of a\nnewspaper simply means that the in\nstitution employs union men, pays\nunion wages, and i3 what is commonly\ncalled a \"fair shop.\"\nThat is the situation with the Her\nald, and the union label, which by\nthe way, is shown at the head of\nmany of the great newspapers, is\nmerely an evidence of \"where we are\nat.\" Fremont (Neb.) Daily Herald.\nFAIR CONTRACTORS.\nList of Those Who Employ Union Car\npenters On All Work.\nBulletin No. 3, Carpenters'. Union,\nLocal 1Q55,,, Lincoln, Nebraska. Phones\nAuto 3S24; Bell F1154, 130 South\nEleventh street.\nThe following employers and con\ntractors have been declared fair by\nCarpenters' Union, Logal 1055, and we\nrequest all parties contemplating\nbuilding or repairs of any kind per\ntaining to our trade to please take no\ntice and consider the following reput\nable contractors and builders befo're\nletting your work.\nAtterbury, H. B., 1901 S St.,\nAuto 5402.\nBaker, S. W., Auto 2040, 1836 South\n5th St.\nChappell, H. E., Bell L-1635, 114\nSo. 13th, room 26.\nCampbell, A., 2950 Holdrege St.\nCopeland, S. R., Auto 3590, 110 No.\n!7th St.\nDrybbro, L., Auto 3861, 432 So. 10th\nDobbs, H., Auto 3935, 329 South 27th\nSt.\nHarrison, T. B., Bell F-351, Brownell\nBlk, room 12.\nHammond Burford, Auto 4997,\n3135 Dudley St.\nHutton, Alex, Auto 2565, 1436 N St.\nJewell, J. W., AutO 3458, 2509 Q St\nJensen, L., Auto 3458, 2509 N St.\nKiewit, A., Bell A-1601, 1620 N St.\nLindell, C. A., Auto 6378, 2739 Sum\nner Ot.\nMcDougal, G. J.\nMeyers, A. L., Auto 4260, 223 No.\n8th St.\nMitchner, E., Auto 6345, 928 South\n2th St.\nMellor, Chas., Auto 2009, 2149 So.\nI5th St.\nOdell, F Auto 3094, 1335 No. 24th\nst.\nMyers, J., Auto 3065, 701 Pine St.\nRyman, C. W., Auto 3903, 1112 Pine\nSt.\nRush, D. A., \"Bell B-1792, Normal.\nSchaull Asenmacher.\nTownsend, T. K., Auto 1505, 1328\nGriffin Loan Company\n.Phones: Bell 313; Automatic 2438. Booms 1, 2 and 3.\n1136 0 Street\n4 'v \"V.\nI i\nWe loan on iurniture, pianos, tirgans,\nwagons, buggies, warehouse receipts, live\nstock and other personal property. We\noffer you\nBest Terms, Prompt Service,\nUnequaled rates, absolute privacy, any\namount, on any payments, any time\n00000OffiOSO0Oi0OSO\nLYRIC THEATRE\nPOLITE VAUDEVILLE\nLincoln's Pnnnlar Plathnuse.\nSouth 15i.h St. V\nVanderveer, O. W., 134 S. 18. Bell\n22C8.\nWebb, S. A., 2743 W., Auto 4226.\nWatson, Joe, Auto 3189, 405 So. 2Cth\nSt.\nLincoln Sash Door Cc, for mill\nwork 2nd Y, Auto 3463.\nParks, A. N., 1 545 O.\nPettit Co., cabinet makers, 1530\nN, Auto 25S2.\nQuick Barr, Belmcnt, 3G03 No. 9.\nBell A-1704.\nWilliams Simpson, 2933 Clinton.\nThis bulletin is issued by authority\nof Carpenters' Uunion, and is subject\nto revision at their orders. Firms and\ncontractors can have names inserted\nby applying to Carpenters' Business\nAgent, at 130 No. 10th street, or by\nphone Auto 3601, Bell F-2239.\nCAPITAL AUXILIARY.\nOur last meeting was held at the\nhome of Mrs. Thompson, 402 South\nTwenty-flvSh street, Friday, Septem\nber 27, and notwithstanding the pour\ning rain, eight faithful souls attended\nand were well paid for their bravery\nin many ways.\nA short husiness session was held,\nfollowed by a very social one, in which\nwe were all pleased to have Mrs\nBustard with us again.\nThe next meeting, Friday, October\n11, will be with Mrs. G. M. Wathaii,\n1744 Garfield street. Take South Sev\nenteenth street car.\nThe \"Long Tramp club\" has been\norganized by a few Auxiliary members\nand their husbands living in Printer-\nville. the purpose of which is to com-\nmune with nature these beautiful fall\ndays. If you can walk ten miles you\nare eligible.\nMrs. George Freeman is entertain\ning relatives from Galesburg, 111.\nMrs. Bustard expects to leave soon\nfor Washington state to snenrl th\nwinter with her mother and sister.\nMrs. Lloyd McKinney has returned\nfrom a two weeks' visit to' Belleville,\nKans.\nMr. J. Rock Williams, father of Mrs\nC. E. Barngrover, made a short yisii\nin Lincoln last week on his way to\nattend the carnival in Omaha.\nA committee expects ito arrange for\na social in the near future. Rumor\nsays \"we need some money in -the\ntreasury, so have your suggestions\nready at the next meeting.\nMRS. C. B. RIGHTER.\nTHE CRIME OF CHILD LABOR.\nIf there is a crime that should bring\nto the cheelv of society the crimson, of\nshame, that orime is the crime of child\nlabor. In spite of so called legislation\nagainst it child labor is on the in\ncrease. The only thing the present\nlegislation is doing is to make per-\nrjurers, of poverty stricken, mothers\nwho lie about their children's ages.\nThe capitalist wants cheap labor,\nwhether it be that of man or woman,\nblack or white,: adult or chi'd.\nSwitchmen's Journal.\nHUNTING FOR NEWS.\nLouis Taylor,, secretary of the Lin\ncoln local of the Commercial Teleg\nraphers' Union, is at work again. But\npot at the telegraph key. Not on\nyour life! He is now on the re\nportorial staff of the Star and is mak\ning good at every turn of the road.\ni\nO O 00OffiO050ffiO0000\nMatinee 3:00 P. M.\nEvening 7:45 9:00 I\n1\nPrices llwavs the Same 10. 15 nts. 9.","height":"25304","width":"19264"}}
